My biggest problem with the piece right now is that it feels unfinished. A monster preying on a small town for years provides opportunities for local legends, agents exploring the town, cults, interviews with old timers who saw the beast, and a lot of thick atmosphere and tension that builds up to the first encounter with the Crooked Man. But this article jumps right to the monster and the D-class' encounter with it, which ruins a lot of the potential horror and then isn't really able to build it back up.







